1) Object and Class Example: Initialization
through reference
Initializing an object means storing data into the object. Let's see a simple
example where we are going to initialize the object through a reference
variable.
File: TestStudent2.java
class Student{
int id;
String name;
}
class TestStudent2{
public static void main(String args[]){
Student s1=new Student();
s1.id=101;
s1.name="Sonoo";
System.out.println(s1.id+" "+s1.name);//printing members with a white space
}
}


Output:
101 Sonoo


We can also create multiple objects and store information in it through
reference variable.


class Student{
int id;
String name;
}
class TestStudent3{
public static void main(String args[]){
//Creating objects
Student s1=new Student();
Student s2=new Student();
//Initializing objects
s1.id=101;
s1.name="Sonoo";
s2.id=102;
s2.name="Amit";
//Printing data
System.out.println(s1.id+" "+s1.name);
System.out.println(s2.id+" "+s2.name);
}
}
Output:
101 Sonoo
102 Amit



